First, we will determine the U.S. dollars we can get per one Canadian dollar. We will divide the one Canadian dollar by the spot exchange rate of Can $1.29. The spot exchange rate is the value of the Canadian dollar per U.S.. dollar.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{U.S. Dollar \$} &= \dfrac{\text{1 Can\$}}{\text{Spot Exchange Rate}}\\[10pt]
&= \dfrac{\text{1 Can\$}}{\text{Can\$ 1.29}}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\text{\$ 0.7752}}
\end{aligned}$$

We will determine the value of Can\$2.50 express in U.S. We have already determined in the previous question that the exchange rate of 1 Canadian dollar to U.S dollar is 1 Can$ = $0.7752.  Therefore, we will multiply the Can$2.50 to the value of Canadian dollars to U.S dollars to the price of the beer.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Canadian Dollar (Can\$)} &= \text{Can\$ in dollar} \times {{\text{Can\$ to exchange}}}\\
&= \text{\$ 0.7752} \times {{\text{Can\$2.50}}}\\
& = \boxed{\text{\$1.938}}
\end{aligned}$$
